Abstract¶

Micronutrients in the human body interact and are interacted with in myriad ways, and as such accurately predicting their conectrations in the body is quite difficult and prone to error.

Analysis was run on a dataset from a previous study by Nierenberg et al. (1989), the objective being to attempt to suitably model retinol concentrations in human plasma (the target feature), and identify statistically significant predictors. After data preparation and exploration, Multiple Linear Regression was applied to generate a suitable model, which was then simplified using backwards feature selection.

The reduced model was weak, only explaining 8.9% of variability in plasma retinol concentrations. It also tended to overestimate low observations of the target feature and underestimate high ones. As such, the final model is not assessed as a a particluarly effective predictor of plasma retinol concentrations. Despite its flaws, the model did manage to support some existing knowledge in the field and determine which features of the dataset were statistically significant, namely age, caloric intake, alcohol consumption, dietary fat and dietary fibre.

Source and Description

Analysis in this report centres on the dataset plasma_retinol (sourced from OpenML (2020) and available from https://www.openml.org/d/511) which, while not officially published, formed the basis of a related study ‘Determinants of plasma levels of beta-carotene and retinol’ by Nierenberg et al. (1989).

The dataset was assembled from a cross-sectional study that took place over three years on patients who underwent elective surgery for the removal or biopsy of a benign lesion from one of multiple specified areas of the body (Stukel, T., 2001). The dataset reports three-hundred-and-fifteen observations of fourteen features which the original research team had reason to believe were related to or affected the concentrations of micronutrients in human plasma. The study measured concentrations of multiple micronutrients, however only those for retinol (a common form of vitamin A) and beta-carotene were included in the final dataset and related paper (Stukel, T., 2001).

The 15 features collected for each observation are summarised in the table below.

Feature Data type Units Description
AGE Discrete Years ($y$) Subject’s age
SEX Nominal 1=“Male”, 2=“Female” Subject’s biological sex
SMOKSTAT Ordinal 1=“Never”, 2=“Former”, 3=“Current Smoker” Subject’s smoking status
QUETELET Continuous $kgm^{-2}$ Subject's Body Mass Index (BMI)
VITUSE Ordinal 1=“Yes, fairly often”, 2=“Yes, not often”, 3=“No” Subject’s use of vitamin supplements
CALORIES Continuous calories ($Cal$) Subject’s caloric intake per day
FAT Continuous grams ($g$) Subject’s dietary fat intake per day
FIBER Continuous grams ($g$) Subject’s dietary fibre intake per day
ALCOHOL Continuous unknown; most likely standard drinks Subject’s alcohol consumption per week
CHOLESTEROL Continuous milligrams ($mg$) Subject’s dietary cholesterol intake per day
BETADIET Continuous micrograms ($\mu g$) Subject’s dietary beta-carotene intake per day
RETDIET Continuous micrograms ($\mu g$) Subject’s dietary retinol intake per day
BETAPLASMA Continuous nanograms per millilitre ($ngml^{-1}$) Subject’s plasma beta-carotene concentration
RETPLASMA Continuous nanograms per millilitre ($ngml^{-1}$) Subject’s plasma retinol concentration

Figure 1.1: Summary of features in the plasma_retinol dataset. The target feature, RETPLASMA is shown in bold. Source: Stukel, T. (2001)

As the dataset technically contains dual target features—RETPLASMA and BETAPLASMA—only one, RETPLASMA has been chosen as the focus of this report. This means that the analysis that follows will aim to explore and model concentrations of the micronutrient retinol in human plasma.

Objectives ¶

The objective of this report is to determine a suitable model based on Multiple Linear Regression that is able to identify signifcant predictors of and explain variability in the target feature—plasma retinol levels in humans—based on measurable biological and lifestyle factors.

After necessary data preparation is complete, this objective will be approached by first, conducting statistical exploration of the dataset. Like all great doers of statistics, we must walk before we can run multiple linear regressions. Exploration of the dataset will enable a deeper understanding of its properties and should thus inform our decisions as we move on.

Most importantly, Multiple Linear Regression will be employed to construct a suitable model for plasma retinol levels in human plasma. Once a suitable model has been finalised, we will analyse its suitability for our objectives and explore what it reveals about the data.

Features¶

Identifiers: We first check the dataset for any features that act as unique observation (or row) identifiers. From a Machine Learning perspective, these are meaningless and must be excluded at the outset. It can be seen from the preview above that the dataset does not contain any features that act as unique identifiers for each observation.

Note that the row numbers on the left are displayed by the Pandas module for ease of reference—they are not a feature of the dataset.

Constance: We are also concerned with ensuring that no features display a constant value. This can be seen by inspection, but for the sake of being thorough and to establish a method for use on future projects, a simple iterative block can confirm this.

In [3]:

Relevance: As mentioned earlier, the dataset technically has dual target features—RETPLASMA and BETAPLASMA—with RETPLASMA having been selected as the target of this report. As such, we remove the BETAPLASMA feature from the dataframe, as we do not wish to include it as a predictor for the target feature of retinol concentrations in plasma RETPLASMA.

The natural question now is whether or not it makes sense to include the feature BETADIET in our model. With limited medical knowledge it would be remiss of us to simply drop the feature because we presume that dietary beta-carotene intake has no effect on levels of other micronutrients—specifically retinol—in plasma.

To determine at least rudimentarily if this is a reasonable presumption, a brief look at the relationship between BETADIET and target feature RETPLASMA is warranted.

The very weak gradient (-0.0019) represented by the BETADIET coefficient does not indicate a relationship. The second key property here is the model's $R^2$ value. An $R^2$ of 0.00 indicates that none of the variablity in RETPLASMA is explained by variablity in BETADIET. As if that weren't enough, we note a very high p-value of 0.811 as well. Granted we have only attempted to establish a linear relationship, but for our purposes, this is sufficient evidence that the BETADIET feature can't reasonably be expected to be a predictor of our target feature RETPLASMA, and so we also remove the BETADIET feature from our dataframe.

Outliers¶

Outliers have the potential to wreak havoc on a model if left unchecked.

As such, numerical outliers will be identified using Tukey's (1977) fences; defining outliers as any values less than $Q_1 - 1.5\times IQR$ or greater than $Q_3 + 1.5\times IQR$.

Outliers will then be Winsorised (Tukey, 1961)—put through a simple clamping transformation to reassign them the closest non-suspect value.

Before we identify and handle outliers, it is apparent that AGE is a feature where some slight outliers may still represent valid data, so let us determine if it is prudent to apply the same treatment to the AGE feature. Handling of slight outliers may not be warranted.

In [9]:
#Assemble a summary of relevant descriptive stats of the AGE feature
min = data["AGE"].min()
max = data["AGE"].max()
print(f"The minimum age is {min} and the maximum age is {max} years.")
Q1 = data["AGE"].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = data["AGE"].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1
upper = Q3 + 1.5*IQR
lower = Q1 - 1.5*IQR
print(f"The lower outlier threshold is {lower} and the upper outlier threshold is {upper} years.")

The minimum age is 19 and the maximum age is 83 years.
The lower outlier threshold is 3.75 and the upper outlier threshold is 97.75 years.

Even though our dataset doesn't contain any, we can see that it might be possible that values lying outside our thresholds are still valid ages. If hypothetically our dataset did contain reasonable age values that fell outside the thresholds calculated, it might be reasonable to apply a slightly different clamping transformation.

We now apply an implementation of our outlier handling algorithm to the remaining numerical features.

In [10]:
#Identify and handle outliers in numerical features
numerical_features = ["QUETELET","CALORIES","FAT","FIBER","ALCOHOL","CHOLESTEROL","RETDIET","RETPLASMA"]

# Iterate through features
for feature in numerical_features:
    counth = 0
    countl = 0
    Q1 = data[feature].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = data[feature].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    upper = Q3 + 1.5*IQR
    lower = Q1 - 1.5*IQR
    # Iterate through observations of the current feature
    for i in range (0, data.shape[0]-1):
        if data.at[i, feature] > upper:    # Clamp high outliers
            data.at[i, feature] = upper
            counth += 1
        elif data.at[i, feature] < lower:    #Clamp low outliers
            data.at[i, feature] = lower
            countl += 1
        else:
            pass
    # Provide some feedback on the process
    if counth > 0 and countl > 0:
        print(f"{feature}: clamped {counth} high and {countl} low outliers.")
    elif counth > 0:
        print(f"{feature}: clamped {counth} high outliers.")
    elif countl > 0:
        print(f"{feature}: clamped {countl} low outliers.")
    else:
        print(f"{feature}: no outliers identified.")

QUETELET: clamped 15 high outliers.
CALORIES: clamped 8 high outliers.
FAT: clamped 10 high outliers.
FIBER: clamped 8 high outliers.
ALCOHOL: clamped 30 high outliers.
CHOLESTEROL: clamped 9 high outliers.
RETDIET: clamped 8 high outliers.
RETPLASMA: clamped 8 high outliers.

We can now progress, satisfied that we have handled any outliers in the plasma_retinol dataset.

Figure 4.7: Pair grid showing correlation and scatterplots between each pair of numerical features, as well as histograms of each single numerical feature.

Unforunately Figure 4.7 doesn't show any obvious relationships of particular relevance. There are some clear correlations between dietary features, which are expected given their related nature. As mentioned during data preparation, we may see some multicollinearity in these dietary features. Under the assumption that most people eat an averagely balanced diet, their dietary intake of macro- and micronutrients might thus be reasonably predicted simply from their caloric intake, CALORIES. As such we suspect that if we see multicollinearity between these features, the following relationships will be at work:

  • FAT $\propto$ CALORIES
  • CHOLESTEROL $\propto$ CALORIES
  • FIBRE $\propto$ CALORIES
  • RETDIET $\propto$ CALORIES

Most other plots appear to be quite random. Although those involving the ALCOHOL feature have a peculiar form, which exhibits little variation from plot to plot. As a result, we suspect that a subject's weekly alcohol intake is fairly independent of the other features in the dataset. Let's take a closer look.

We have previously identified the dataset's categorical features as SEX, SMOKSTAT, and VITUSE, and we can see above that these are already of the correct data type. The former is nominal and requires one-hot-encoding, the latter two are ordinal and will require integer-encoding.

Backwards Feature Selection for the Reduced Model¶

First, why choose this approach? Backwards feature selection is used because for our purposes it presents as significantly less laborious than forwards feature selection. And why the p-value approach specifically? We determine that as this project is not necesssarily Machine-Learning-focused, we are most concerned with determining the statistically significant features affecting plasma retinol levels, moreso than we are with pure prediction accuracy.

Aksakalli et al. (2020) provide a fantastic block of code for automatic backwards feature selection, and such is its elegance that we would be remiss not to make use of it. The code loops over the full fitted model, sorting features in descending order of p-value, removing the top (highest p-value) feature if its p-value > level of significance (0.05), and refitting the model. It continues until no p-values exceeding the significance level remain, and then returns the reduced fitted model for use as model_reduced_fitted.

In [31]:
## Code in this block is sourced from Aksakalli et al. (2020). It has been adapted in style
## only to match other code in this report, otherwise it remains unchanged.
## WARNING 1: The code below assumes that the Intercept term is present in the model.
## WARNING 2: It will work only with main effects and two-way interactions, if any.

# Create the patsy model description from formula
patsy_description = patsy.ModelDesc.from_formula(formula_string)

# Initialize feature-selected fit to full model
linreg_fit = model_full_fitted

# Carry out backwards feature elimination based on p-values
p_val_cutoff = 0.05

print("\nPerforming backwards feature selection using p-values:")

while True:
    #print(linreg_fit.summary())
    pval_series = linreg_fit.pvalues.drop(labels="Intercept")
    pval_series = pval_series.sort_values(ascending=False)
    term = pval_series.index[0]
    pval = pval_series[0]
    if (pval < p_val_cutoff):
        break
    term_components = term.split(':')
    print(f'\nRemoving term "{term}" with p-value {pval:.4}')
    if (len(term_components) == 1):    # This is a main effect term
        patsy_description.rhs_termlist.remove(patsy.Term([patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[0])]))    
    else:                              # This is an interaction term
        patsy_description.rhs_termlist.remove(patsy.Term([patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[0]), 
                                                        patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[1])]))    
        
    linreg_fit = smf.ols(formula=patsy_description, data=data_encoded).fit()
    
# Perform MLR on the clean fit after backwards elimination of features
model_reduced_fitted = smf.ols(formula = patsy_description, data = data_encoded).fit()

print("\n")
print(model_reduced_fitted.summary())
print(f"\nRegression number of terms: {len(model_reduced_fitted.model.exog_names)}")
print(f"Regression F-distribution p-value: {model_reduced_fitted.f_pvalue:.4f}")
print(f"Regression R-squared: {model_reduced_fitted.rsquared:.4f}")
print(f"Regression Adjusted R-squared: {model_reduced_fitted.rsquared_adj:.4f}")

Condition Checking¶

The validity of a multiple regression model hinges on key conditions that must be met before we can begin analysing a model:

Linearity: The data should show a linear correlation between explanatory and response variables. This is assessed using a plot of residuals. If the correlation were non-linear we would expect to see non-linearity in the residual plot as the model tried to describe a non-linear relationship with a straight line.

In [33]:
# Generate a scatter plot of Predicted vs. Actual RETPLASMA for the reduced model
plt.scatter(residuals_reduced["PREDICTED"], residuals_reduced["RESIDUAL"], alpha=0.3);
plt.xlabel("Pred. RETPLASMA (ng/ml)");
plt.ylabel("Residuals (ng/ml)")
plt.title("Figure 5.4: Residuals vs. Predicted RETPLASMA for reduced model")
plt.show();

The residuals don't exhibit any clear trend and are distributed fairly evenly around the zero-line, which implies linearity.

Independence: We assume that residuals are independent because observations in the original study and thus our dataset are presumed to be independent.

Nearly normal residuals: Distirbution of residuals must be nearly normal. We check for normality of residuals by generating a histogram using the Seaborn module.

In [34]:
# Generate a histogram of residuals of the reduced model
sns.distplot(residuals_reduced["RESIDUAL"], kde=True).set(title=
    "Figure 5.5: Histogram of Residuals for reduced model", xlabel="Residuals (ng/ml)", ylabel="Frequency")
plt.show;

Some right-skewness can be observed, but residuals appear to be sufficiently normal.

Constant variablity: Variability of points around the least-squares line must remain roughly constant. This implies that the variability of residuals should be roughly constant too, so we can confirm using another residual plot.

In [35]:
# Generate a scatter plot of Residuals vs. Predicted RETPLASMA for reduced model

plt.title("Figure 5.6: Residuals vs Predicted RETPLASMA for reduced model")

plt.show();

The plot of Residuals vs. Predicted RETPLASMA is indicative of constant variability as the residuals appear in roughly even proportions and distances on either side of the zero-line.

We can now be satisfied that our reduced model has passed the condtion checks.

Analysis and Conclusions

"And if you labelled your axes, I could tell you exactly how MUCH better." Source: Munroe (2010)

We summarise the results of the reduced model as such:

  • The $R^2_{adj}$ value of 0.089 suggests that 8.9% of variability in RETPLASMA is explained by variability in the remaining explanatory features.
  • The Intercept occurs at 441.99 with the 95% confidence interval placing it between 337.96 and 546.03. It has little meaning independent of the explanatory features, zero-values for which would imply illogicalities such as an age of 0 and no calories consumed per day.
  • AGE has a coefficient of 3.15 (95% confidence interval between 1.72 and 4.58) implying a 1 year increase to age predicts an increase of 3.15$ng$ of retinol per $ml$ of plasma, all else being equal.
  • CALORIES has a coefficient of 0.12 (95% confidence interval between 0.023 and 0.225) implying a 100 calorie increase per day predicts an increase of 12$ng$ of retinol per $ml$ of plasma, all else being equal.
  • FAT has a coefficient of -2.15 (95% confidence interval between -3.82 and -0.48) implying a 1 gram increase in daily fat intake predicts a decrease of 2.15$ng$ of retinol per $ml$ of plasma, all else being equal.
  • FIBRE has a coefficient of -6.35 (95% confidence interval between -11.99 and -0.72) implying a 1 gram increase in daily fibre intake predicts a decrease of 6.35$ng$ of retinol per $ml$ of plasma, all else being equal.
  • ALCOHOL has a coefficient of 10.46 (95% confidence interval between 3.28 and 17.63) implying an extra standard drink per week predicts an increase of 10.46$ng$ of retinol per $ml$ of plasma, all else being equal.

The number of features in the model has been reduced significantly, and $R^2$ values have taken a small hit (-0.2%). As stated above though, $R^2_{adj}$ shows that 8.9% of variation in RETPLASMA is still explained by variation in the remaining explanatory features, an acceptable loss considering we have eliminated six features.

We note that FIBER which had a marginal p-value of 0.05 in the full model has been retained and now exhibits a significant p-value of 0.027.

It is surprising to see that two of the features eliminated by backwards feature selection were VITUSE and the dummy of SEX, as correlations between each of these and the target feature RETPLASMA were identified during data exploration. It can be surmised that this occurred because these features had high associated p-values. High p-values should not be interpreted as a lack of correlation between the feature in question and the target feature, instead they imply that in this particular model the VITUSE and SEX features were not statistically significant due to the effects of the other included features.

We had suspected some collinearity between the dietary features CALORIES, FAT and FIBER however it can be seen that the coefficient of the caloric intake feature (0.12) expresses a fairly weak positive effect on plasma retinol levels, while coefficients for fat and fibre intake (-2.14 and -6.35) imply robust negative effects on the target feature. This is surprising and implies that while increasing caloric intake predicts only a very mild increase in plasma retinol concentrations, increasing fat and fibre intakes predicts a fairly substantial decrease in retinol concentrations. AGE is also significant in the model, with a one year increase predicting an increase of 3.15$ng$ of retinol per $ml$ of plasma, holding the rest equal.

The full model we generated was able to explain 9.1% of variability in plasma retinol concentrations, but included several features that were not statistically significant at the 0.05 significance level. After backwards feature selection, our reduced model included six fewer variables but still explained 8.9% of variability in the target feature as being attributable to variability in the remaing other features.

Unfortunately this is quite low, so while we have achieved the objective of generating a suitable model with the dataset at hand, it does not seem that the features of the dataset on their own are useful for accurately predicting retinol concentrations in plasma. The model is valid after checking conditions but tends to overestimate low RETPLASMA values and underestimate high ones. Despite this, it exhibits at least one relationship that is supported by the science:

The coefficient on the weekly alcohol intake feature ALCOHOL indicates a strong positive relationship between alcohol consumption and plasma retinol levels. As first glance this seems counterintuitive: increased consumption of alcohol, widely proven to negatively affect health, predicts increased levels of the vitamin A form retinol in plasma. The model shows that this occurs to the effect of 1 more standard drink per week predicting an increase of 10.5$ng$ of retinol per $ml$ of plasma. According to Clugston and Blaner (2012) "research supports the notion that chronic alcohol consumption precipitates a decline in hepatic retinoid levels through increased breakdown, as well as increased export to extra-hepatic tissues". We believe increased export to extra-hepatic (i.e. non-liver) tissues is the key here, as more retinol making its way outside the liver implies more retinol being transported in the blood and thus the plasma. This was confirmed by a doctor (J. Warren, personal communication, October 31, 2020) and as such we are very pleased to see that even though it is weak, our model is reflective of the science at play in this field.

The final model, which explains 8.9% of variability in the RETPLASMA feature is:

$${plasma\space retinol\space concentration} = 441.99 + 3.15\times age + 0.12\times calories + (-2.15)\times fat + (-6.35)\times fibre + 10.46\times alcohol$$

The objective of determining some potentially significant predictors of plasma retinol concentrations has thus been achieved. As has been stated above, they are age, caloric intake, alcohol consumption, dietary fat and dietary fibre.
